The paper presents a Python library for unsupervised learning on graph-structured data using discrete substructure patterns and neural language models. This suggests that the paper could belong to several arXiv CS sub-categories, including Machine Learning (cs.LG), Computation and Language (cs.CL), Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI), Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), and Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS). Among these, Machine Learning (cs.LG) is the most likely category as the paper focuses on learning representations using the distributive hypothesis. Computation and Language (cs.CL) is also likely as the paper uses neural language models. Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) is another possible category as the paper deals with unsupervised learning. Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) is relevant as the paper deals with graph-structured data. Finally, Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) is also possible as the paper presents efficient implementations of popular graph decomposition algorithms.
